#compdef ruler
# =============================================================================
# ruler — Eleanor Berger's (intellectronica) "Ruler — apply
#         the same rules to all coding agents" — a
#         TypeScript-Node CLI that synchronizes "instruction
#         files" across multiple AI coding assistants
#         (Cursor, Claude Code, GitHub Copilot, Aider,
#         Continue, Codex, Cline, RooCode, Windsurf, Zed
#         Agent Panel, and more).  Edit ONE source of truth
#         in .ruler/ directory; ruler propagates to each
#         agent's native config format (.cursorrules,
#         CLAUDE.md, .github/copilot-instructions.md,
#         .aider.conf.yml, etc.).
#         Distinguishing from AGENTS.md proposals, manual
#         file copying, and per-agent CLI tools by:
#           - MULTI-AGENT SYNCHRONIZATION — single .ruler/
#             directory contains AGENTS.md + ruler.toml +
#             arbitrary .md instruction files; ruler apply
#             generates each agent's native config file
#             from these sources
#           - 18+ SUPPORTED AGENTS (as of 0.3.42):
#               * Cursor      (.cursorrules / .cursor/rules)
#               * Claude Code (CLAUDE.md)
#               * GitHub Copilot (.github/copilot-instructions.md)
#               * Aider       (.aider.conf.yml +
#                              CONVENTIONS.md)
#               * Continue.dev (.continuerules)
#               * Codex CLI   (.codex/instructions.md)
#               * Cline       (.cline/rules)
#               * RooCode     (.roo/rules)
#               * Windsurf    (.windsurfrules)
#               * Zed Agent Panel
#               * JetBrains AI Assistant
#               * Goose
#               * Gemini CLI
#               * Cody
#               * AmazonQ
#               * GitLab Duo
#               * Aria (Opera)
#               * Cursor Tab
#           - TOML CONFIG via .ruler/ruler.toml — declarative
#             agent selection + per-agent overrides:
#               default_agents = ["cursor", "claude", "copilot"]
#               [agents.cursor]
#               enabled = true
#               output_path = ".cursor/rules/main.mdc"
#               [agents.aider]
#               enabled = false
#           - MCP (Model Context Protocol) PROPAGATION via
#             --mcp / --no-mcp — additionally syncs MCP
#             server definitions to each agent's
#             mcp-server-config location
#           - --mcp-overwrite — replace native MCP config
#             instead of merging
#           - 3 ROOT COMMANDS via yargs v18:
#               * apply        — generate agent-specific
#                                files from .ruler/
#               * init         — scaffold .ruler/ in project
#                                or in --global XDG_CONFIG_HOME
#               * revert       — remove ruler-generated
#                                content from agent configs
#           - APPLY OPTIONS:
#               --project-root DIR       (default cwd)
#               --agents LIST            (comma-separated agent IDs)
#               --config PATH            (TOML config file path)
#               --mcp / --no-mcp         (enable MCP propagation)
#               --mcp-overwrite          (replace MCP not merge)
#               --gitignore / --no-gitignore
#                                        (auto-add generated paths)
#               --gitignore-local        (write to .git/info/exclude)
#               -v / --verbose
#               --dry-run                (preview without writing)
#               --local-only             (ignore global ~/.ruler)
#               --nested                 (load nested .ruler dirs)
#               --backup / --no-backup   (.bak files)
#               --skills / --no-skills   (skills support — experimental)
#               --subagents / --no-subagents (subagents — experimental)
#           - INIT OPTIONS:
#               --project-root DIR       (default cwd)
#               --global                 (init in XDG_CONFIG_HOME/ruler)
#           - REVERT OPTIONS:
#               --project-root DIR
#               --agents LIST
#               --config PATH
#               --keep-backups
#               -v / --verbose
#               --dry-run
#               --local-only
#           - GLOBAL + LOCAL CONFIG — supports XDG_CONFIG_HOME/
#             ruler/ for cross-project rules + per-project
#             .ruler/ for project-specific overrides;
#             --local-only disables global config
#           - NESTED RULE LOADING via --nested — descendant
#             .ruler/ directories merged into root rules for
#             monorepo-style project structures
#           - BACKUP FILES via --backup (default on) — saves
#             .bak files when overwriting existing agent
#             configs; restored by revert + --keep-backups
#           - DRY-RUN MODE via --dry-run — preview which
#             files would be written without making changes
#         Used by: developers using multiple AI coding
#         assistants who want consistent context across
#         tools, team leads enforcing project conventions
#         (CONVENTIONS.md style) across all team members'
#         agent configs, and as a reference implementation
#         of @iarna/toml + yargs + multi-agent config
#         synchronization in TypeScript-Node.
#
# Author:  Eleanor Berger (intellectronica on GitHub) —
#          UK-based AI tooling researcher, runs
#          ai.intellectronica.net.  Released ruler ~2024;
#          rapid adoption (2728+ stars).  Current version
#          0.3.42; active development through 2026.  License:
#          MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/intellectronica/ruler
#          https://github.com/intellectronica/ruler/blob/main/src/cli/commands.ts
#          https://github.com/intellectronica/ruler/blob/main/src/cli/index.ts
#          https://github.com/intellectronica/ruler/blob/main/package.json
#          https://ai.intellectronica.net/ruler
# CLI:     src/cli/commands.ts — uses yargs v18 (well-
#          documented elsewhere).  Headline library:
#          **@iarna/toml** (the new variant being documented
#          here, completing Axis 25 three-language symmetry
#          across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: @iarna/toml (https://github.com/iarna/iarna-toml —
#          "Better TOML parsing and stringifying all in that
#           familiar JSON interface" — Rebecca Turner
#           (iarna on GitHub).  Distinct from toml (R689,
#           Rust Axis 25 opener) and BurntSushi/toml (R690,
#           Go Axis 25 expansion) by being:
#              1. TOML 1.0 SPEC COMPLIANT — implements TOML
#                 v1.0.0 spec (and the post-1.0 draft
#                 features in some releases).  Distinct from
#                 the older 0.4.0-targeted Node TOML
#                 libraries (toml-node, toml-j0.4).
#              2. JSON-LIKE API — modeled after JSON.parse /
#                 JSON.stringify for familiarity:
#                   import TOML from '@iarna/toml';
#                   const obj = TOML.parse(text);
#                   const text = TOML.stringify(obj);
#                 Same mental model as JavaScript developers
#                 already know.
#              3. STREAMING ASYNC API — uniquely among Axis
#                 25 variants, @iarna/toml offers both
#                 synchronous AND async streaming parsing:
#                   import TOML from '@iarna/toml/async';
#                   const obj = await TOML.parse.stream(stream);
#                 Suitable for large TOML files where
#                 blocking the event loop is undesirable.
#                 Distinct from toml-rs (sync only) and
#                 BurntSushi/toml (sync only).
#              4. PRESERVES KEY ORDER — output preserves the
#                 insertion order of keys; Cargo.toml-style
#                 round-tripping without scrambling sections.
#                 Same as Rust toml-rs's preserve_order
#                 feature; Go BurntSushi/toml also preserves
#                 order via reflection.
#              5. NATIVE Date FOR DATETIMES — TOML datetime
#                 types decode to JavaScript Date objects
#                 (with appropriate timezone handling).
#                 Distinct from toml-rs's
#                 toml::value::Datetime (separate type)
#                 and BurntSushi/toml's native time.Time.
#              6. STRICT SPEC ADHERENCE — rejects malformed
#                 TOML that other Node parsers might accept;
#                 errors include line + column for parse
#                 failures.  Same strict philosophy as
#                 toml-rs + BurntSushi/toml.
#              7. ZERO BABYLON DEPS in v2 — @iarna/toml v2
#                 dropped its single dependency, becoming a
#                 truly zero-dependency package (just stdlib).
#                 Same minimalism as terkelg/prompts (R663)
#                 + Paul Miller's noble-* libraries.
#              8. NPM ECOSYSTEM ADOPTION — used by npm itself
#                 (the Node.js package manager) for parsing
#                 its own internal config files + Cargo.toml-
#                 style file processing in npm workflows.
#                 Also used by Yarn, ESLint, Mocha, and
#                 thousands of other tools.
#              9. WIDELY USED IN BUILD TOOLS — Vite, Rollup,
#                 esbuild, Turborepo, and many bundlers use
#                 @iarna/toml for parsing their own .toml
#                 config files when present.
#             10. REBECCA-TURNER / iarna ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE
#                 — Rebecca Turner (iarna on GitHub) was a
#                 long-time npm Inc. engineer (joined 2014,
#                 contributed to npm CLI core).  Also
#                 maintains:
#                   * @iarna/toml             — TOML parser  (THIS)
#                   * gauge                   — progress bar
#                                                (used by npm)
#                   * are-we-there-yet        — npm progress
#                   * promise-call-limit      — concurrency limits
#                   * stream-uri              — streaming URI
#                                                fetcher
#                   * write-file-atomic       — atomic file writes
#                   * npm-registry-fetch      — npm registry HTTP
#                 Distinct from Isaac Schlueter (npm founder),
#                 Sindre Sorhus (Node CLI utils), Vitaly
#                 Puzrin (markdown-it / js-yaml), Evgeny
#                 Poberezkin (ajv), Lovell Fuller (sharp),
